#Summary and distribution of the housing price data. The data shows that there are some extreme outliers that are strongly
#inflencing the mean value (the summary shows that the maximum value is $7,700,000)


housing_df$price %>% summary()
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  75000  321950  450000  540088  645000 7700000 
#In order to prevent extreme outliers from influencing the data, multi-million dollar housing have been filtered out.
#The all housing data above $1,500,000 have been filtered out. $1,500,000 was chosen as the threshold to account for high cost of living areas.Properties with sqft_living above 5,000 have been filtered out to avoid the influence of extreme outliers.

housing_df_filtered <- housing_df %>% filter(price <= 1500000, sqft_living < 5000)

#Create new dataframes using above filters and also filtering for whether a property is water front or non-waterfront.

df_no_waterfront_filtered <- housing_df_filtered %>% filter(waterfront == "0")
df_waterfront_filtered <- housing_df_filtered %>% filter(waterfront == "1")

#function to analysis the sequence_along of various segments of the housing data.

housing_data_sequence <- function (data, col){
  
  print_sequence <- data %>% ggplot(mapping = aes_string(x= col %>% seq_along(), y = col))+
    geom_jitter (alpha = .5) + 
   geom_smooth(method="loess") +
   theme_classic() +
   labs(title=str_c("Natural sequence of ", col, " data"),
       subtitle="Using seq_along()")
  
  print_sequence %>% print()
  
}

housing_df %>% housing_data_sequence("bedrooms")

housing_df %>% housing_data_sequence("floors")

housing_df %>% housing_data_sequence("bathrooms")

housing_df %>% housing_data_sequence("price")

housing_df %>% housing_data_sequence("sqft_living")

housing_df %>% housing_data_sequence("sqft_lot")



#Violin plot to analysize housing data
housing_plot <- function(data, x_col,y_col){
  
  print_housing <- data %>% ggplot(mapping = aes_string(x = x_col, y= y_col))+
    geom_violin(draw_quantiles = c(0.25, .05, 0.75),
                fill = 'blue', alpha = 0.3, size = 1.0)+
    labs(title = "Housing data analysis",
         subtitle = str_c("relationship between ", x_col, " & ", y_col))
  
  print_housing %>% print()
  
}


housing_df_filtered %>% housing_plot("view", "price")

housing_df_filtered %>% housing_plot("grade" ,"price")

housing_df_filtered %>% housing_plot("condition" ,"price")

housing_df_filtered %>% housing_plot("waterfront", "price")

Hypothesis Testing

#Question: Is there a statistically significant difference in mean home price between waterfront and non-waterfront properties in the dataset?

#Null hypothesis = Waterfront properties would have a statistically significant greater mean sale price than non-waterfront properties in the dataset.

#Alternative hypothesis = non-waterfront properties would have a statistically significant greater mean sale price than waterfront properties in the dataset.

#The results of the two-sided t.test performed show that there is a statistically significant difference between the sales price of waterfront properties and non-waterfront properties

#creating dataframes that filter out waterfront/non-waterfront properties.

df_waterfront <- housing_df %>% filter(waterfront == "1")
df_no_waterfront <- housing_df %>% filter(waterfront == "0")

plot.sqft_vs_price <- function(df_housing){
  df_housing %>% ggplot(aes(sqft_living, price)) + 
    geom_point(size = 2)+
    geom_line(aes(sqft_living, score.price), size = .5, color = "red")+
  labs(title = "Sqft_living vs. Price score prediction for non-waterfront properties")

#Histograms functions to show the distribution of bathrooms and bedrooms data


#Histogram functions to show the distribution of the normalized/non-normalized bathroom and bedroom data.

plot.hists <- function(columns1, df_house, bins = 20){
  plot1 <- ggplot(df_house, aes_string(columns1)) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), bins = bins,
                   alpha = .3, color = 'green') +
    geom_density(size = 1)+
    labs(title=str_c("Histogram and density function \n for ", columns1),
         x=str_c("value of ", columns1))
  
  plot1 %>% print()
}


plot.hists_norm <- function(columns1, df_house, bins = 20) {
  
  plot2 <- ggplot(df_house, aes_string(columns1)) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), bins = bins,
                   alpha = .3, color = 'green')+
    geom_density(size = 1)+
    labs(title=str_c("Histogram and density function \n for normalized ", columns1),
         x=str_c("value of ", columns1))
  
  plot2 %>% print()
}

columns1 <- c('sqft_living', 'bathrooms', 'bedrooms')
columns1 %>% walk(plot.hists, df_no_waterfront_filtered)

columns1 %>% walk(plot.hists_norm, df_no_waterfront_filtered_norm)


#Function to create the plots to graph the relationship between housing price and the number of bedrooms/bathrooms

plot.line_housing <- function(columns1, df_housing) {

    labs(title = str_c("Relationship between ", columns1, " and prices for non-waterfront properties"),
         x=columns1, y="Price")

  plot3 %>% print()
